<!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>The supplement industry didn't discover the brain. It discovered a second market. Creatine had spent three decades as an unglamorous white powder in gym bags — cheap, abundant, genuinely effective for explosive muscle performance. Then someone in a marketing meeting noticed that the brain runs on ATP too, and the rebranding began. "Cognitive health." "Neural energy support." "Nootropic performance." The powder didn't change. The price did. So did the claims. The global creatine market, worth roughly $640 million in 2024 according to Grand View Research, is growing at double-digit rates — and the brain angle is the engine. In November 2024, Europe's primary food safety regulator reviewed the evidence and concluded that no cognitive benefit had been established. The market grew anyway.</p>
</section>

<section id="mechanism-is-real" class="reveal">
  <h2>The mechanism is legit, sure — but it's got hard limits that the hype conveniently ignores.</h2>
  <p>The brain consumes roughly 20% of the body's total energy. It runs on ATP. Creatine, through the creatine kinase system, helps regenerate ATP rapidly when demand spikes — during intense activity, a cognitive load, a period of metabolic stress. This is textbook bioenergetics, not marketing copy. The mechanism exists.</p>
  <p>The catch is anatomical. Almost 95% of the body's creatine is stored in skeletal muscle, not the brain. The brain synthesizes most of its own creatine locally, making it substantially less dependent on dietary intake than muscle tissue is. When you swallow creatine, the molecule has to cross the blood-brain barrier to reach neurons — and the transporter responsible for that crossing, SLC6A8, sits in the endothelial cell layer of the barrier but is absent from the surrounding astrocyte feet. CNS uptake from the periphery is, as researchers at the University of Basel described in a 2024 sleep-deprivation study, "marginal and takes a long time." The brain is, by design, resistant to exogenous creatine.</p>
  <p>This creates a dosing problem the marketing doesn't mention. The standard creatine dose for muscle performance is 3–5 grams per day. Studies that have demonstrated meaningful increases in brain creatine concentrations — typically 3–10% above baseline — have mostly used 20 grams per day or more. The EFSA review noted that the one study showing a working memory effect in sleep-deprived individuals used 20 grams per day for seven days: a dose 6.7 times higher than what's typically sold as a "brain health" supplement. Your morning scoop of cognitive clarity is not the dose that moved the needle in the lab.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The brain is resistant and less reliant on exogenous creatine ingestion." — Gordji-Nejad et al., Scientific Reports, 2024</p></aside>

<section id="what-evidence-shows" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the evidence actually shows</h2>
  <p>In November 2024, the European Food Safety Authority published its scientific opinion on whether creatine supplementation improves cognitive function. The EFSA panel reviewed twenty-three human intervention studies, including the meta-analyses circulating as proof of the brain benefit. Its conclusion: "A cause-and-effect relationship has not been established between creatine supplementation and an improvement in cognitive function in one or more of its domains."</p>
  <p>What the panel found was a pattern that repeats throughout the cognitive enhancement literature: small studies, heterogeneous populations, multiple endpoints tested without correction for multiplicity, and effect sizes that erode under scrutiny.</p>
  <p>The most cited positive findings trace back to studies of stressed individuals. After 24–36 hours of sleep deprivation combined with moderate exercise, 20 grams per day of creatine improved working memory performance in young male adults. Creatine at the same dose attenuated cognitive decline under acute oxygen deprivation. A 2024 trial in Basel gave participants a single high dose — approximately 0.35 grams per kilogram of body weight, or roughly 25 grams for a 165-pound person — before a 21-hour sleep-deprivation protocol and detected increased brain creatine levels and improved processing speed. These are real findings. They demonstrate something genuine: when the brain's energy system is under metabolic stress, supplementing the creatine pathway may partially compensate.</p>
  <p>That's a very specific claim. It's also not the one being sold.</p>
</section>

<section id="meta-analyses-problems" class="reveal">
  <h2>The meta-analyses that didn't survive peer review</h2>
  <p>Two meta-analyses dominate the pro-creatine narrative. Both have serious problems that rarely make it into the social-media summary.</p>
  <p>The Prokopidis et al. (2023) meta-analysis in <em>Nutrition Reviews</em> concluded that creatine supplementation improved memory in healthy individuals. It was widely cited. Shortly after publication, a letter in the same journal identified a unit-of-analysis error: multiple cognitive subtests from the same participants had been treated as independent effect sizes — a statistical practice known as double-counting that inflates both precision and apparent effect. When the authors re-analyzed their data using appropriate methods, the overall effect on memory was no longer statistically significant. The one exception that survived the correction: older adults aged 66–76.</p>
  <p>The Xu et al. (2024) meta-analysis in <em>Frontiers in Nutrition</em> — based on sixteen randomized controlled trials — went further, claiming significant positive effects on memory, attention time, and processing speed. But a 2026 commentary identified the same double-counting problem: "Several included trials report multiple correlated cognitive outcomes from the same participants, yet these outcomes are treated as independent effect sizes." The EFSA had already flagged this in its 2024 opinion, concluding that the meta-analysis "inflated sample sizes" and that "no conclusions can be drawn" from it for substantiating a cognitive health claim. For good measure, Xu et al.'s own 2025 corrigendum corrected its processing speed findings, which had stated the wrong conclusion due to a translation error. No significant impact on processing speed remained after correction.</p>
  <p>The result is that the most frequently cited positive evidence base is, upon examination, flawed in its statistical architecture and rejected by Europe's primary food safety regulator. McMorris et al., whose independent 2024 systematic review in <em>Behavioural Brain Research</em> was funded by no commercial entity, summarized the state of affairs plainly: the research "fails to support the theoretical basis for an effect on cognition" in unstressed populations, while providing "somewhat equivocal results" even for stressed ones.</p>
</section>

<div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>What the EFSA actually found</strong></p><p>The European Food Safety Authority's 2024 review of creatine and cognitive function — triggered by an application from Alzchem Trostberg GmbH, a creatine manufacturer — concluded that no cause-and-effect relationship between creatine supplementation and cognitive improvement could be established. The panel noted that the only meaningful cognitive effect in healthy individuals occurred at 20 g/day during extreme sleep deprivation combined with exercise — six times the dose marketed for cognitive benefits, in conditions that do not describe most buyers.</p></div>

<section id="who-benefits-from-the-product" class="reveal">
  <h2>Who the science actually describes</h2>
  <p>Older adults show the most consistent signal. The Prokopidis et al. re-analysis retained its finding in adults aged 66–76 even after statistical correction: this is a population in which brain creatine levels decline with age, dietary intake may be lower, and the system has less metabolic reserve. A 2025 systematic review on creatine and cognition in aging concluded that 'moderate cognitive benefits, particularly for memory and processing speed, in older adults — especially those with low baseline creatine' represents the most defensible claim in the literature (citation unverified).</p>
  <p>Vegetarians and vegans represent another plausible beneficiary group. Dietary creatine comes predominantly from meat; people who don't eat it have measurably lower muscle and brain creatine at baseline. The Benton and Donohoe (2011) study found cognitive improvements specifically in vegetarians who supplemented, but a 2023 replication attempt in the Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition failed to confirm these effects, highlighting the need for updated evidence.</p>
  <p>Beyond these groups: individuals under acute metabolic stress — severe sleep deprivation, hypoxia, sustained cognitive load — may gain something from supplementation, particularly at higher doses. The evidence is thin, methodologically imperfect, and concentrated in conditions most people don't regularly inhabit.</p>
  <p>The population none of this describes is a well-nourished 25-year-old who eats meat, sleeps adequately, and is deciding whether to upgrade from their gym creatine to a premium "nootropic" formula at three times the price. For that person, the honest answer from the current literature is: probably nothing. The energy system isn't the limiting factor in their cognition. Creatine supplementation doesn't enhance a brain that's already running at its ceiling.</p>
</section>

<section id="who-benefits-from-belief" class="reveal">
  <h2>Who profits when you believe otherwise</h2>
  <p>Consider who triggered the EFSA review. Alzchem Trostberg GmbH — a German company that manufactures creatine — submitted the application to authorize a cognitive health claim. The primary supporting evidence they offered was the Xu et al. (2024) meta-analysis. The EFSA rejected that meta-analysis for statistical errors. The Nutrients (2021) narrative review most widely cited in favor of creatine's brain effects lists, in its conflict-of-interest disclosures, authors who received research grants, creatine donations, travel support, speaking honoraria, and advisory board positions from AlzChem. The same company that submitted the health claim application. Reviewing, in effect, its own case.</p>
  <p>None of this proves the findings are wrong. Industry funding doesn't automatically manufacture false results. But it creates systematic pressure toward positive interpretations, away from publishing null results, and toward framing modest or context-dependent effects as significant. A 2025 critical perspective in <em>The Journal of Nutrition</em> named the dynamic directly: commercial enthusiasm has "far exceeded the strength of the supporting evidence" — and this gap persists because ambiguity, not clarity, serves the seller. A definitive null result closes a market. A contested, apparently-promising literature keeps it open. "More research is needed" sustains sales while the debate continues.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"A cause-and-effect relationship has not been established between creatine supplementation and an improvement in cognitive function." — EFSA Panel on Nutrition, Novel Foods and Food Allergens, 2024</p></aside>

<section id="what-to-conclude" class="reveal">
  <h2>The users the evidence describes</h2>
  <p>Creatine is safe. For muscle performance, the evidence is extensive and the result is not in dispute. The brain question is different — and the honest version of it is more specific than anyone selling you a "nootropic" wants to admit.</p>
  <p>If you are an older adult — roughly 65 and above — the evidence for modest memory benefit is the most durable finding in the literature. If you are a vegetarian or vegan with chronically low dietary creatine, supplementation may matter. If you are consistently sleep-deprived or under sustained cognitive stress, higher-dose creatine may partially compensate — though the dose required is likely well above what you're taking.</p>
  <p>If you are a healthy young adult eating meat and sleeping adequately, taking 3–5 grams per day because a wellness influencer cited "neural energy": the current evidence does not support that. Not because creatine is unsafe, but because your brain is already producing what it needs. You can't enhance a system that isn't the limiting factor.</p>
  <p>When you encounter the next meta-analysis showing impressive cognitive benefits, check who funded it. Then ask the question that the marketing apparatus cannot answer cleanly: if the effect were as strong as the packaging implies, why does it tend to disappear when the researchers have no financial stake in the outcome? The evidence isn't a conspiracy — it's a product of institutional pressures that distort supplement research broadly and reliably. The mechanism is real. The effect size, in the population being most aggressively sold to, is not. The industry depends on you conflating those two things. You don't have to.</p>
</section>

